Project 4: Featurization and Model Tuning Project¶

The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled). The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).

Data Description:¶

Domain: Cement manufacturing¶

Context:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Attribute Information:¶

Cement:measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Blast: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Fly ash: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Water: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Superplasticizer: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Coarse Aggregate: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Fine Aggregate: measured in kg in a m3 mixture¶

Age: day (1~365)¶

Concrete compressive strength: measured in MPa¶

Learning Outcomes:¶

Exploratory Data Analysis Building ML models for regression Hyper parameter tuning

Objective:¶

Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning

Step 1¶

c. Pick one strategy to address the presence outliers and missing values and perform necessary imputation (10 marks)

There are no any missing values in the dataset. If missing values exists, those can be imputed based on the median of the column and be replaced with median.¶

For outliers use zscore from stats.zscore and remove the data with more han 3 standard deviations, also use IQR and remove values which are below 1.5 IQR i.e. of 25% quantile and above 1.5 IQR above 75 % quantile.¶

Dtree regressor model performance for original data¶

In [161]:
# configure bootstrap
n_iterations = 1000              # Number of bootstrap samples to create
n_size = int(len(Data3) * 0.50)    # picking only 50 % of the given data in every bootstrap sample

# run bootstrap
stats = list()
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # prepare train and test sets
    
    train = resample(values, n_samples=n_size)  # Sampling with replacement 
    test = np.array([x for x in values if x.tolist() not in train.tolist()])  # picking rest of the data not considered in sample
    # fit model
    model = DecisionTreeRegressor()
    model.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1])
    # evaluate model
    predictions = model.predict(test[:,:-1])
    score = r2_score(test[:,-1], predictions)    # caution, overall accuracy score can mislead when classes are imbalanced
    if i%10==0:
        print(score)
    stats.append(score)

# configure bootstrap
n_iterations = 100              # Number of bootstrap samples to create
n_size = int(len(Data3) * 0.50)    # picking only 50 % of the given data in every bootstrap sample

# run bootstrap
stats = list()
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # prepare train and test sets
    
    train = resample(values, n_samples=n_size)  # Sampling with replacement 
    test = np.array([x for x in values if x.tolist() not in train.tolist()])  # picking rest of the data not considered in sample
    # fit model
    modelLR = LinearRegression()
    modelLR.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1])
    # evaluate model
    predictions = modelLR.predict(test[:,:-1])
    score = r2_score(test[:,-1], predictions)    # caution, overall accuracy score can mislead when classes are imbalanced
    if i%10==0:
        print(score)
    stats.append(score)

Conclusion and observations¶

Five models have been tested on all the original features after removal of outliers and scaling was applied.

  1. Linear regression accuracy (train=77,test=76) LR with PCA Accuracy (tran=72,test=76)
  2. Linear regression with polynomial terms with degree=2, interaction_only=True is considered Accuracy (train=99,test=99)
  3. Decision tree regressor Accuracy (train=75,test=71) for original scaled and preprocessed data Accuracy (train=97,test=95) on selected scaled features including polynomial features
  4. Random forest regressor Accuracy (train=95,test=84) original preprocessed and scaled data
  5. SVR regressor Accuracy (train=91, test = 87) on original scaled data Accuracy (train=60,test=61)on selected scaled features including polynomial features

From the above experimentation and results, it shows that :¶

  1. Linear regression with polynomial terms gives better accuracy for both train and test data(99% for both). The data was preprocessed with removal of outliers and scaling was applied.
  2. Also DTree regressor on selected scaled features including polynomial features shows good accuracy
  3. SVR shows weak performance than other models used but random forest performs better than SVR
